{{Expand Japanese|豊鍬入姫命|1=Toyosukiiri-hime}} {{Infobox royalty | title = {{ill|Saigū (priestess)|lt=Saigū|en}} | image = File:Hibara-jinja, torii closeup.jpg|thumb|240x240px | caption = {{ill|Hibara Shrine|ja|檜原神社}} at the foot of {{ill|Mount Miwa|en}} in {{ill|Sakurai, Nara|lt=Sakurai|en}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en}}. The shrine is identified as the place where the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi were first enshrined after they were removed from the imperial palace. | successor = {{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|en}}| | house = {{ill|Imperial House of Japan|en}} | father = {{ill|Emperor Sujin|en}} }} {{complex}}
{{Nihongo|{{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Toyosukiiri-hime|ja|豊鍬入姫命|fr}}|豊鍬入姫命[[Category:11]][[ja:豊鍬入姫命]][[Category:11]][[en:draft:Toyosukiiri-hime]]}} was a Japanese mythological figure and [[princess|princess]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=KansaiOdyssey |date=2017-07-26 |title=Oh Gods! The Tales of Omononushi |url=https://kansai-odyssey.com/oh-gods-the-tales-of-omononushi/ |access-date=2023-10-03 |website=Kansai Odyssey |language=en-US}}</ref>. She was the first {{ill|Ise Saiō|lt=Saigū|en}},<ref name="Saigū | 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム-2022" />
Her brother was the similarly named {{ill|Toyokihiribiko no Mikoto|ja|豊城入彦命|1=Toyokiirihiko-no-Mikoto}}
== Mythical narrative == {{Further|Mount Miwa|Ōmononushi|Ise Saiō}} Amaterasu ({{ill|Shintai|lt=via the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi sword|en}}) and {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Yamato Okunitama|lt=Yamato-no-Okunitama|ja|倭大国魂神|simple}}, the {{ill|tutelary deity|en}} of Yamato, were originally worshipped in the great hall of the imperial palace.<ref name="aston-1896a">{{cite wikisource|year=1896|plaintitle=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wslink=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wspages=151-154|chapter=Book I|publisher=Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.|author-first=William George|author-last=Aston}}</ref><ref name="meiji-japan-society-1925a">{{cite book |title=Kogoshūi: Gleanings from Ancient Stories. Translated with an introduction and notes |date=1925 |publisher=Meiji Japan Society |pages=29–30 |translator1-last=Katō |translator1-first=Genchi |translator2-last=Hoshino |translator2-first=Hikoshirō}}</ref> [[fr:Toyosukiiri-hime]] {{ill|Tatari|lt=Pestilence|en}} struck during the 5th year of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|lt=Sujin's|en}} rule, killing half the Japanese population. The following year peasants abandoned their fields and rebellion became rampant.<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book |author=Aston, William George. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2 |date=1896 |publisher=The Japan Society London |isbn=9780524053478 |pages=150–164 |author-link=William George Aston}}</ref> To help relieve the suffering of his people, the Emperor turned his attention towards the gods. At the time, both the sun goddess {{ill|Amaterasu|en}} and the god {{Nihongo|{{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Yamato Okunitama|lt=Yamato-no-Okunitama|ja|倭大国魂神|simple}}|倭大国魂神}} were enshrined at the Imperial Residence. Sujin became overwhelmed with having to cohabit with these two powerful deities and set up separate enshrinements to house them. Am