{{Nihongo|{{ill|Toyosukiiri-hime|ja|豊鍬入姫命|fr}}|豊鍬入姫命}} was a Japanese mythological figure and [[princess|princess]]<ref>{{Cite web |last=KansaiOdyssey |date=2017-07-26 |title=Oh Gods! The Tales of Omononushi |url=https://kansai-odyssey.com/oh-gods-the-tales-of-omononushi/ |access-date=2023-10-03 |website=Kansai Odyssey |language=en-US}}</ref>. She was the first {{ill|Ise Saiō|lt=Saigū|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}},<ref name="Saigū | 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム-2022" />

Her brother was the similarly named {{ill|Toyokihiribiko no Mikoto|ja|豊城入彦命|1=Toyokiirihiko-no-Mikoto|1=Toyokiirihiko-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

== Mythical narrative ==
{{Further|Mount Miwa|Ōmononushi|Ise Saiō}}
Amaterasu ({{ill|Shintai|lt=via the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi sword|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) and {{ill|Yamato Okunitama|lt=Yamato-no-Okunitama|ja|倭大国魂神|simple}}, the {{ill|tutelary deity|en}} of Yamato, were originally worshipped in the great hall of the imperial palace.<ref name="aston-1896a">{{cite wikisource|year=1896|plaintitle=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wslink=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697|wspages=151-154|chapter=Book I|publisher=Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.|author-first=William George|author-last=Aston|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref><ref name="meiji-japan-society-1925a">{{cite book |title=Kogoshūi: Gleanings from Ancient Stories. Translated with an introduction and notes |date=1925 |publisher=Meiji Japan Society |pages=29–30 |translator1-last=Katō |translator1-first=Genchi |translator2-last=Hoshino |translator2-first=Hikoshirō}}</ref>

{{ill|Tatari|lt=Pestilence|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} struck during the 5th year of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|lt=Sujin's|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} rule, killing half the Japanese population. The following year peasants abandoned their fields and rebellion became rampant.<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book |author=Aston, William George. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ |title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2 |date=1896 |publisher=The Japan Society London |isbn=9780524053478 |pages=150–164 |author-link=William George Aston}}</ref> To help relieve the suffering of his people, the Emperor turned his attention towards the gods. At the time, both the sun goddess {{ill|Amaterasu|en}} and the god {{Nihongo|{{ill|Yamato Okunitama|lt=Yamato-no-Okunitama|ja|倭大国魂神|simple|qq=draft|qq=draft}}|倭大国魂神}}  were enshrined at the Imperial Residence. Sujin became overwhelmed with having to cohabit with these two powerful deities and set up separate enshrinements to house them. Amaterasu was moved to {{Nihongo|Kasanui village|笠縫邑}} in {{ill|Yamato Province|en}} (Nara), where a {{ill|Himorogi|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} altar was built out of solid stone.<ref name="aston150–164" /> Sujin placed his daughter {{Nihongo|{{ill|Toyosukiiri-hime|ja|豊鍬入姫命|fr}}|豊鍬入姫命|1=Toyosukiiri-hime}} in charge of the new shrine, and she would become the first {{ill|Ise Saiō|en}},<ref name="Saigū|國學院大學デジタルミュージアム-2022">{{Cite web |date=2022-05-22 |title=Saigū {{!|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8608 |access-date=2023-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220522022806/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/?id=8608 |archive-date=2022-05-22}}</ref>entrusting with her the {{ill|Yata no Kagami|lt=mirror|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kusanagi no Tsurugi|lt=sword|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, she brought  them to the {{Nihongo|Kasanui village|笠縫邑}}.<ref name="aston-1896a" /><ref name="meiji-japan-society-1925a" />

She moved across many {{ill|Moto-Ise Shrines|ja|元伊勢|1=Moto-Ise Shrines|simple|User:Immanuelle/Moto-Ise Shrines|en:draft|qq=draft|qq=draft}} throughout her life.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Kidder |first=J. Edward |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7pEOicqsjv0C&dq=%22Moto-Ise%22&pg=PA201 |title=Himiko and Japan's Elusive Chiefdom of Yamatai: Archaeology, History, and Mythology |date=2007-02-28 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=978-0-8248-3035-9 |language=en}}</ref>

During the reign of Sujin's son and successor, {{ill|Emperor Suinin|en}}, custody of the sacred treasures were transferred from Toyosukiirihime to Suinin's daughter {{ill|Yamatohime-no-mikoto|lt=Yamatohime|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who took them first to "Sasahata in Uda" to the east of Miwa. Heading north to {{ill|Ōmi Province|lt=Ōmi|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, she then eastwards to {{ill|Mino Province|lt=Mino|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and proceeded south to {{ill|Ise Province|Ise|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where she received a revelation from [[Amaterasu|Amaterasu]]:

{{quotation|Now Ama-terasu no Oho-kami instructed Yamato-hime no Mikoto, saying:—"The province of Ise, of the divine wind, is the land whither repair the waves from the eternal world, the successive waves. It is a secluded and pleasant land. In this land I wish to dwell." In compliance, therefore, with the instruction of the Great Goddess, a shrine was erected to her in the province of Ise. Accordingly an {{ill|Abstinence Palace|en}} was built at Kaha-kami in Isuzu. This was called the palace of Iso. It was there that Ama-terasu no Oho-kami first descended from Heaven.<ref>{{cite wikisource|author-first= William George |author-last= Aston |chapter= Book I |wslink= Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |plaintitle= Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697 |year= 1896 |publisher= Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co.|wspages=176|qq=draft|qq=draft}}</ref>}}

This account serves as the origin myth of the {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Grand Shrine of Ise|en|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Amaterasu's chief place of worship.

